A new science
This summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, researchers gathered to ponder the necessity of a new science that could be just as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a hundred years ago.
The majority of scientists believe that the fundamental questions of the sciences have been answered.
In light of the great challenges, it is believed that there is little left to discover.
The remaining questions can be grouped into three categories: First, the great unsolved mysteries of science (such as the unification of gravity and electricity in a single theory), whose exploration requires enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World. Second, data collection, which refers to work related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies. Third, problems whose solutions must be based on scientific foundations, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
In addition, people are of the opinion that the only difficult part of the work would be to use already known natural laws for the benefit of humanity with the help of new technologies.
Who could deny that?
Today's models do work.
However, a growing group of scientists points to phenomena that are not well explained by today's theories.
These problems occur more and more frequently, but are also skillfully circumvented, because there is simply no science that could explain these problems.
This lack of science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
In the individual scientific disciplines, the knowledge is somewhat well established.
Physics, at least the part of it with which we ordinary mortals are confronted, is well researched.
Chemistry and biochemistry are also built on solid foundations – although there are still a few things in our body that we do not yet fully understand, it can be assumed that the basic mechanisms of interaction between cells and molecules are known.
In addition, there are the new social sciences, which deal with people and societies.
In each of these fields – physics, biochemistry, and social sciences – the theories are well-established and are largely beyond dispute.
Every discipline has its own language and its own mechanisms.
In the rarest of cases is a scientist an expert in more than one field, because these worlds and languages are simply so different.
That means we cannot find answers to complex questions that require the involvement of multiple disciplines.
One might, for example, think of the brain.
This complex organ consists of molecules whose interaction is based on the principles of physics. The information conveyed in this process is transmitted according to the laws of electricity.
In addition, there is a system of specialized cells that communicate by exchanging chemical substances and also transmit information in this process.
In the interaction between two brains, a new level emerges: Here, information exchange takes place through language, symbols, and concepts.
At each level, it is about the exchange of information, and there are appropriate theories that explain the processes at each individual level.
Information is also exchanged between the individual levels, but there is no science that could even begin to explain this information exchange.
To compensate for this deficiency, some scientists have attempted to redefine the instruments for explaining processes within a single level, so that they could then be applied to another level.
These experiments then lead to something like a "language" at the cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes this "transplantation" of explanatory patterns works quite well, but the fundamental problem remains unsolved: What form does the information exchanged between the individual levels take, and how is it transmitted?
Now, almost all systems of the world consist of such layers.
And in all cases, there is this degrading lack of knowledge about how the entire system functions.
The group of interdisciplinary scientists who met in Paris formed loosely under the name "Foundations of Information Science."
The researchers come from various countries and disciplines and have been collaborating on a decentralized basis for eight years.
In addition to scientists from the relevant disciplines, art theorists, psychiatrists, language experts, and philosophers are beginning to participate in the discourse.
The majority of the group relies on this "transplantation strategy," in which the scientific foundations of one level are adapted and supplemented and then transferred to another level.
Others, on the other hand, consider a completely new approach to be necessary.
In their view, many scientific norms are the product of historical accidents and new ways of thinking are needed.
If the FIS group is lucky, new radical approaches emerge from scientists who currently lack access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Fully free thinking is an underestimated factor.
Almost all activities that take place under the banner of "science" have developed an institutional character, similar to their counterparts in the world of economics.
One believes that developing countries must build up similar resources as industrialized countries. However, this could stifle creative thinking.
Many young scientists are currently experiencing a revolution, and many of these – sometimes revolutionary – ideas come from laboratories and research centers that are not connected to the major institutions.
The most sophisticated approaches in the field of mathematical algorithms came for twenty years from the Soviet Union, where there was a severe shortage of computing power everywhere.
The most brilliant and literally world-changing discoveries in physics over the last few decades did not come, as expected, from the well-known innovation centers, but from Budapest.
In Iran, there is an architectural tradition that has contributed to important insights for cognitive scientists.
And the most radical new ideas in the field of second-generation artificial intelligence (the so-called "autonomous agents") come from Prague today.
The most creative scientific achievements entered history.
When Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, he thereby changed the identity of space and time. The FIS conference in July was the unannounced beginning of an attempt to redefine the universe in this way.
Those gaps were identified that require explanations.
More scientists from innovative regions will be added to this group, in order to then identify the problems that could be solved once this new science is developed, or discover them, as one might say.
